04589nam a22005775i 9780889209442DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20012001xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892094427 a10.51644/97808892094422doi  a(DE-B1597)667224  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aDU880b.E92 2009 7aBUS0230002bisacsh04a306/.0996122211 aEvans, Mike, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPersistence of the Gift :bTongan Tradition in Transnational Context /cMike Evans. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (220 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction — Recentring the Periphery -- tEconomic Development in Polynesia -- tSocial Structure and Organization during the Contact and Early Post-Contact Period -- tEuropean Contact and the Transformation of the Traditional Polity -- tContemporary Social Organization among Village Commoners -- tThe Island Economy -- tGift Exchange and Ceremony -- tConclusion — By Their Actions Ye Shall Know Them -- tA Comparison of the Population and Demography of Ha’ano Island and the Kingdom of Tonga As a Whole -- tGlossary of Tongan Terms -- tConfiguration of Households — Pila and Leti -- tNotes -- tReferences Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTonga, the South Pacific island kingdom located east of Fiji and south of Samoa, is one of the world’s few remaining constitutional monarchies. Although Tonga has long been linked to the world system through markets and political relationships, in the last few decades emerging regional and global structures have had particularly intense and transformative effects. Today, because of greatly increased labour migration, people, money, and resources are in constant circulation among Tonga, New Zealand, Australia, and the United States. In Persistence of the Gift, Evans provides a detailed ethnographic and historical analysis of how, in spite of superficial appearances to the contrary, traditional Tongan values continue to play key roles in the way that Tongans make their way in the modern world. But this ethnography is neither that of a timeless “ethnographic present” nor of a remote coral atoll. Instead, like the inhabitants of Tonga themselves, the monograph begins in the islands, and works outward, tracing how Tongans seek to meet their own, culturally specific goals, within the constraints, challenges, and opportunities of the world system. Tongan culture, like our own, continues to transform in the face of global change, but the changes experienced by Tongans everywhere are patterned and managed by the values of Tongan agents. Both creative and conservative, the emerging transnationalist system continues to be discernibly and proudly Tongan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCeremonial exchangexTongaxHa'ano Island. 0aCeremonial exchangezTongazHa'ano Island. 0aÉchange cérémonielxTongaxHa'ano. 4aBusiness & Economics: Economics. 4aEthnography. 4aPolitical Science. 4aSocial Science: Anthropology. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920944240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889209442423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889209442/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-de